<subSubSection pageId="106" pageNumber="107" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="106.[151,1437,290,1180]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,290,316]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Remarks</emphasis>
. The subgenus is cosmopolitan and rich in species (approximately 50 accepted species to date, cf. Van Soest 
<emphasis box="[219,276,326,352]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">et al.</emphasis>
2020), but it is likely to be non-monophyletic (
<bibRefCitation author="Loh, T. L. &amp; Lopez-Gentil, S. &amp; Song, B. &amp; Pawlik, J. R." box="[810,989,326,352]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="205 - 217" refId="ref134173" refString="Loh, T. L., Lopez-Gentil, S., Song, B. &amp; Pawlik, J. R. (2012) Phenotypic variability in the Caribbean Orange Icing sponge Mycale laevis (Demospongiae: Poecilosclerida). Hydrobiologia, 687, 205 - 217. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10750 - 011 - 0806 - 1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Loh 
<emphasis box="[864,914,326,352]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). The tangential ectosomal skeleton is a disorganized mass of single intercrossing spicules. Many species have a grooved surface and often have a full complement of spicules, mycalostyles, several sizes of anisochelae and of sigmas and often trichodragmas. Toxas are rare. The smallest anisochelae may frequently have their lower alae reduced to a single stick-like extension of the shaft crowned by a small spur. These features are shared with species of subgenera 
<taxonomicName authority="Hentschel, 1929" authorityName="Hentschel" authorityYear="1929" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Oxymycale">
<emphasis box="[1079,1311,470,496]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Oxymycale)</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hentschel, E." pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="857 - 1042" refId="ref132496" refString="Hentschel, E. (1929) Die Kiesel- und Hornschwamme des N ˆ rdlichen Eismeers. In: R ˆ mer, F., Schaudinn, F., Brauer, A. &amp; Arndt, W. (Eds.), Fauna Arctica. Eine Zusammenstellung der arktischen Tierformen mit besonderer Ber ʾ cksichtigung des Spitzbergen-Gebietes auf Grund der Ergebnisse der Deutschen Expedition in das N ˆ rdliche Eismeer im Jahre 1898. 5 (4). Fischer, Jena, pp. 857 - 1042, pls. XII-XIV." type="book chapter" year="1929">Hentschel, 1929</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="" box="[259,536,506,532]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Rhaphidotheca">
<emphasis box="[259,536,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Rhaphidotheca)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Kent, W. S." box="[542,668,506,532]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="217 - 224" refId="ref133134" refString="Kent, W. S. (1870) On two new Siliceous Sponges taken in the late Dredging-Expedition of the Yacht ' Norma' off the Coasts of Spain and Portugal. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 4, 6 (33), 217 - 224, pl. XV. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222937008696236" type="journal article" year="1870">
<collectingRegion box="[542,599,506,532]" country="United Kingdom" name="Kent" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Kent</collectingRegion>
, 1870
</bibRefCitation>
. With these subgenera 
<taxonomicName authority="(Mycale)" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" baseAuthorityName="Mycale" box="[921,1111,506,532]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[921,1111,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Mycale)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occasionally shares species with size categories of the mycalostyles. In contrast to Hajdu (1995) we employ here categories of mycalostyles only if there is a clear length difference, because width differences are strongly influenced by growth stage of the spicule. Bluntly rounded pointed ends are also considered subject to variation within the same mycalostyle 
<typeStatus box="[1354,1406,614,640]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">type</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="106.[151,1437,290,1180]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
Among the species occurring in the region, there is a puzzling complex formed by specimens having the identical spicule complement of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gray, 1867)" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[479,924,686,713]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="grandis" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[479,767,686,712]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Mycale) grandis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gray, J. E." box="[784,916,686,713]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="492 - 558" refId="ref131696" refString="Gray, J. E. (1867) Notes on the Arrangement of Sponges, with the Descriptions of some New Genera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1867 (2), 492 - 558, pls. XXVII-XXVIII." type="journal article" year="1867">Gray, 1867</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but exhibiting two distinct habitus features, (1) red specimens usually occurring somewhat hidden underneath and between corals, often covered partially by sediment, with a smooth surface showing a faint reticulation, and (2) in contrast white specimens, forming thick cushions in exposed position, with the surface distinctly punctate. Preliminary unpublished molecular sequence data (both of 28S and 18S genes) obtained by us from several red individuals and a single white one show small (2–3) differences in the composition of base pair positions. This induced us to consider these 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[1187,1365,866,892]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="grandis" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[1187,1365,866,892]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">M. (M.) grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms as potentially specifically different, and we chose to name them provisionally 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[1046,1229,902,928]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="grandis" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[1046,1229,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">M. (M.) grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
‘red’ and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1867" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="grandis" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[1348,1437,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">M. (M.)</emphasis>
aff. 
<emphasis box="[198,284,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
‘white’, treated below among the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Mycale)" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1867" baseAuthorityName="Mycale" box="[680,872,938,964]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[680,872,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Mycale)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in alphabetical order. The justification to treat them separately is debatable, because the 
<typeStatus box="[677,725,974,1000]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">type</typeStatus>
material of early species united under 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[1161,1341,974,1000]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="grandis" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[1161,1341,974,1000]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">M. (M.) grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains incompletely known lacking the decisive information on live color. The red and white ‘morphs’ of this complex resemble the orange and white individuals found in the Caribbean 
<taxonomicName authority="(Carter, 1882)" baseAuthorityName="Carter" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[891,1318,1046,1072]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="laevis" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[891,1152,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Mycale) laevis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Carter, H. J." box="[1166,1310,1046,1072]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="346 - 368" refId="ref129390" refString="Carter, H. J. (1882) Some Sponges from the West Indies and Acapulco in the Liverpool Free Museum described, with general and classificatory remarks. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 5, 9 (52), 266 - 301, 346 - 368. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222938209459052" type="journal article" year="1882">Carter, 1882</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, described and investigated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Loh, T. L. &amp; Lopez-Gentil, S. &amp; Song, B. &amp; Pawlik, J. R." box="[376,569,1082,1108]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="205 - 217" refId="ref134173" refString="Loh, T. L., Lopez-Gentil, S., Song, B. &amp; Pawlik, J. R. (2012) Phenotypic variability in the Caribbean Orange Icing sponge Mycale laevis (Demospongiae: Poecilosclerida). Hydrobiologia, 687, 205 - 217. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10750 - 011 - 0806 - 1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Loh 
<emphasis box="[428,484,1082,1108]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
. No distinct genetic groupings were detected in that species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="106.[151,1437,290,1180]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
Less binary color divisions are found in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Dendy, 1905)" baseAuthorityName="Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[645,1140,1118,1145]" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="crassissima" subGenus="Mycale">
<emphasis box="[645,971,1118,1144]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Mycale (Mycale) crassissima</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dendy, A." box="[984,1131,1118,1145]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="57 - 246" refId="ref130615" refString="Dendy, A. (1905) Report on the sponges collected by Professor Herdman, at Ceylon, in 1902. In: Herdman, W. A. (Ed.), Report to the Government of Ceylon on the Pearl Oyster Fisheries of the Gulf of Manaar, 3 (Supplement 18), pp. 57 - 246, pls. I-XVI." type="book chapter" year="1905">Dendy, 1905</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, with color shades varying from orange, via greenish or bluish to whitish. No separate treatment for these are made below.
</paragraph>
